    • ex3

      static void ex3()
      this method covers upper bounded wildcards, which means the type can be subclass of the type. In this example call a method that takes a upper bounded wildcard list of type ? extends Animal, which means this can take a list of Animal or subclass of Animal. In this example we send a list of Animals to the method, and also a list of Dogs to the method (as Dog is a subclass of Animal)
      See Also:
      printUpperBound(List), Animal, Dog, Cat, Poodle

    • printUpperBound

      static void printUpperBound​(List<? extends Animal> animals)
      this method is used by ex3() this is a upper bounded wildcard, it can take a list of Animals or any list of subclass of Animals. A list produced by a wildcard is immutable and cannot change, you can't add to the list. the upper bounded wildcard is <? extends Animal> and can take a Animal or a subclass of Animal, so it can take a List<Animal>, List<Dog>, List<Cat> and List<Poodle> as Animal is the super class and all the other are subclasses of Animal
      See Also:
      Animal, Dog, ex3()

    • ex4

      static void ex4()
      this method shows an example of upper bounded list of type Integer, which means that this can take ANY type of wrapper number. As Number is a super class of all Number wrappers, a upper bounded wildcard of type List<? extends Number> can take Integers, Doubles, etc
      See Also:
      printUpperNumbers(List)

    • printUpperNumbers

      static void printUpperNumbers​(List<? extends Number> numbers)
      this method is used by ex4() this method takes a upper bounded type of List<? extends Number> That means upper bounded for classes and they're sub classes, here is the Number super class and the sub classes of Integer, Double, Short, Byte, etc, but not apparently Long
      See Also:
      ex4()

    • ex5

      static void ex5()
      upperBounded wildcards are also used when you want to create a list of objects that implement a particular interface, you still use the keyword extends. This example calls another method takeFlyer(List<? extends Flyer>flyers) that takes a List of objects that implement flyer interface List<? extends Flyer> classes Plane, Goose and Hanglider all implement Flyer, which means the list sent to the mehod can be one of these types. A List of type Glider can also be sent to this method as Glider is a sub interface of Flyer
      See Also:
      Flyer, Glider, Plane, Goose, Hanglider, takeFlyer(List)

    • takeFlyer

      static void takeFlyer​(List<? extends Flyer> flyers)
      this method is used by ex5() this method takes a list of objects that implement the Flyer interface. This can be a list of objects whose classes implement the Flyer interface (Plane, Goose, Hanglider) or a list of type Glider, as Glider is a sub class of Flyer
      See Also:
      Flyer, Glider, Plane, Goose, Hanglider, ex5()

    • ex6

      static void ex6()
      This mehtod covers lower bounded wildcards, which can only be a particular type or a SUPER CLASS of that type and uses the syntax <? super. i.e in our code we have a Dog class that has a sub class poodle and a super class of Animal, so if we have the type List<? super Dog> this can only be a list of Type Dog or Animal and NOT POODLE (however it has to be noted that you could still add poodles to this list as a poodle is a sub class of Dog, but this poolde added to the list could not access any methods that only exist in the poodle class.
      See Also:
      takeLowerBound(List), Dog, Poodle, Animal, Cat

    • takeLowerBound

      static void takeLowerBound​(List<? super Dog> list)
      this is for usage with ex6() this method takes a loweBounded wildcard and uses the keyword SUPER, this method takes a list of Dogs or objects that are super classes of Dog, So this can take a list of Dogs, Animals and objects
      See Also:
      ex6(), Dog

    • ex8

      static void ex8()
      this covers general information about generics that may not have been covered in all the examples so Far first how you can have a mutable and a immutable reference to the same list (meaning that you can add and remove elements from a list with one reference and not be able to do the same with another reference). also by using the wildcard ?, we will show how to quickly create a immutable list we will also show the practical effects of declaring an object with generics FINAL we also cover the addAll() method of the List class
      See Also:
      Animal
